Work Orders are reviewed, how you can take ownership of a Work Order, and how to defer or update its status to In Progress or Canceled. For more information about this process, please go to Appendix A - Execute Work Business Process to view the flowchart and step narrative. ## User Roles and Responsibilities The audience for this training includes the following user roles: | Role | Responsibility | |---------------------|------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------| | EPS Admin | Reviews,assigns and approvesWork Orders; developsJob Plans; creates PMs (preventive maintenance);prioritizes and schedulesPM Work Orders | | EPS Work Lead | Reviews,assigns, prioritizes and completes Work Orders | | FMAdmin | Receives, classifies and disposes building service equipment(BSE) Assets; reviewsand a

PMs(preventive maintenance) | | HTM Admin | Classifies Assets;reviewsand approves Work Orders; creates PMs (preventive maintenance);approvesPM workdeferrals; creates Job Plans; determinesneedfor decontamination/sanitization of turned in Assets | | HTM Tech | Performswork and completes Work Orders, identifies needto deferwork; updates PMwork status; completes decontaminates/sanitizesWork Orders on turned in Assets | | HTM Tech Plus | Performswork, identifies needto deferwork, and updatesPM work status, work reassignment | | VA Work Order Clerk | Reviewsand evaluates Service Requests;plans and approveswork and assigns Work Orders to HTM shops | ## Learning Objectives - · Describe the process for executing work - · Identify the Work Order review process - · Assign or take ownership of a Work Order - · Demonstrate how to defer or update a Work Order status (to In Progress or Canceled) - · Explain how to create an approved follow-up Work Order ## Agenda | Topic | Estimated Time | |--------

| | IU | In Use | | LO | LoanedOut | | OOS | Out of Service | | PM | Preventive Maintenance | ## REVIEW A WORK ORDER The Admin, Work Order Clerk, Supervisor, or Tech roles will review the Work Order. - · If the Work Order is valid, the Admin, WO Clerk, Supervisor or Tech assigns or takes ownership of the Work Order, which is what we will cover here. - · If the Work Order is not valid, the Admin or Work Order Clerk reviews the invalid Work Order and determines whether it can be edited or must be canceled. - o If the Work Order must be canceled, the Admin or Work Order Clerk changes the Work Order status to 'Canceled.' Refer to the Update Work Order Status section which we will cover later in this lesson. - o If the Work Order can be edited, the Work Order goes back through the Plan and Approve Work Process . ## ASSIGN OR TAKE OWNERSHIP OF A WORK ORDER If the Work Order is valid, the Admin, Work Order Clerk, Supervisor or Tech assigns or takes ownership of the Work Order.

## ASSIGN OR TAKE OWNERSHIP OF A WORK ORDER If the Work Order is valid, the Admin, Work Order Clerk, Supervisor or Tech assigns or takes ownership of the Work Order. Work Orders are scheduled and assigned to a Responsible Tech by the HTM Admin, EMS Admin, and Work Order Clerk. Before assigning ownership to a Work Order and changing the status to In Progress , verify if the Work Order requires any of the following field entries: - · Work Type - · Vendor Support - · Job Plan - · Priority - · Planned Labor/Craft Use the following steps to assign or take ownership of a Work Order: Step 1. From the Start Center , select Work Order Tracking in the Favorite Applications portlet. The Work Order Tracking application opens with the List tab selected. Figure 1. Work Order - List Tab Step 2. On the List tab, enter information into one or more filter fields and press Enter on your keyboard. Select the appropriate Work Order.

Figure 1. Work Order - List Tab Step 2. On the List tab, enter information into one or more filter fields and press Enter on your keyboard. Select the appropriate Work Order. The Work Order opens on the Work Order tab. Figure 2. Work Order List Tab - Filter Fields Step 3. To assign the Work Order to another person, select the Select Owner toolbar. NOTE: For an explanation of the various Work Order Status codes available from the New Status drop-down menu, refer to Appendix B - Work Order Status Codes for details. We will cover below the three most common status codes. - 1. When should you update Work Order Status to In Progress ? INPRG In Progress or Initiated ( ) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either. However, you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - 2. When should you Defer a Work Order (accomplished by updating the PM Results fi

the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - 2. When should you Defer a Work Order (accomplished by updating the PM Results field to DEFER )? DEFER Deferred ( ) indicates that the PM Work Order cannot be completed. This status requires selection of one of the following options in the Deferred Reason field: - · CNL - Could Not Locate - · IU - In Use - · LO - Loaned Out - · OOS - Out of Service - · OTHER - Other NOTE: If the reason the Work Order was deferred is NOT listed in the options available (listed above), select OTHER in the Deferred Reason field and then type the appropriate reason in the Other Deferral Reason field, which is required before the Work Order can be saved. IMPORTANT! This code is used to track all PM Work Orders that are deferred for reasons other than the options available. ## 3. When should you update Work Order Status to Canceled ? CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed an

l PM Work Orders that are deferred for reasons other than the options available. ## 3. When should you update Work Order Status to Canceled ? CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled. If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it, you can change the status to WAPPR (Waiting on Approval) then change to CAN. NOTE: No changes can be made to the Work Order once it has been canceled. The following toolbar icons allow for quick changes to a Work Order status: - · Changes the status to In Progress - · Changes the status to Approved - · Changes the status to Completed ## CREATE AN APPROVED FOLLOW-UP WORK ORDER The most common use cases for creating a follow-up Work Order are: - 1. RK ORDER The most common use cases for creating a follow-up Work Order are: - 1. When you notice during a Preventive Maintenance (PM) that you have something that requires Corrective Maintenance (CM), you will create your CM as a follow-up to your PM. - 2. When you have performed a repair to bring a piece of equipment back into service, however it turned out that it still needs further repairs to be in optimal condition. To create a follow-up Work Order, follow these steps: - Step 1. From the Start Center , select Work Order Tracking in the Favorite Applications portlet. The Work Order Tracking application opens with the List tab selected. Figure 10. Work Order - List Tab Step 2. On the List tab, enter information into one or more filter fields and press Enter on your keyboard. Select the appropriate Work Order. The Work Order opens on the Work Order tab. Figure 11. Work Order List Tab - Filter Fields ## Step 3. From the Select Action menu, select Create and then select Work Order .

The Work Order opens on the Work Order tab. Figure 11. Work Order List Tab - Filter Fields ## Step 3. From the Select Action menu, select Create and then select Work Order . Figure 12. Select Action Menu - Create Work Order Selection NOTE: The Responsible Tech field is automatically populated with the login id of the person who created the follow-up. Step 4. Select the Related Records tab and select the chevron work order. to navigate to the follow-up Figure 13. Related Records Tab Step 5. Assign or Take Ownership of a Work Order. (See earlier Lesson Topic) Step 6. To approve the Work Order, select the Approve Work Order icon on the toolbar. You may also change to a different status as appropriate. See Appendix B and earlier topic within this lesson. ## Step 7. Select OK . IMPORTANT! You do not need to create a Follow-up Work Order if the Work Type of the Work Order is PM and the PM Result is CA - Corrective Action Required .

## Step 7. Select OK . IMPORTANT! You do not need to create a Follow-up Work Order if the Work Type of the Work Order is PM and the PM Result is CA - Corrective Action Required . Maximo automatically generates a follow-up Work Order for this work so no action is required. We will learn more about scheduling PM Work Orders in a future lesson. ## REVIEW ## Knowledge Check ## 'A Minute to Win It' Use your Guide, if needed, to answer the following questions within the minute allowed. - 1. 2 Plan and Approve Work. | ## APPENDIX B - WORK ORDER STATUS CODES Work Order status may be changed by selecting a Change Status icon on the toolbar. Changing the status also saves the Work Order. The following status codes can be used on a Work Order: - · APPR (Approved) indicates the work plan has been approved and the work can begin. You can report actuals against approved Work Orders. Once the status is changed to Approved, the user can no longer delete tasks, labor or materials using the Delete Row (trash can) icon. The user can change the status of individual tasks to Canceled which is similar to deleting a task. The Work Order status can be changed back to Waiting Approval from Approved if other information needs to be modified. However, information cannot be deleted if the Work Order was previously in an Approved status. - · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against

- · CAN (Canceled) indicates the work will not be performed and is canceled . If the Work Order has already been initiated and has actuals reported against it, you cannot change the status to CAN. If the Work Order has already been initiated but does not have any actuals reported against it you can change the status to WAPPR then change to CAN. - · CLOSE (Closed) finalizes and closes the Work Order. No changes can be made to the Work Order. - · COMP (Completed) status indicates all the physical work has been completed . You cannot delete any information on the Work Order when the status is complete, however, information (Log, Labor, Material, etc.) can be added to the Work Order. Once a Work Order has been completed, the only status that it can be changed to is closed. - · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or

- · INPRG (In Progress or Initiated) indicates work has started and is In progress or Initiated . In Progress is similar to Approved in that, you cannot delete tasks, labor or materials. You cannot cancel tasks either, but you can change the status of the Work Order back to Waiting on Approval from In Progress if additional changes need to be made. Note that the only way to go from In Progress to Approved is by changing the status to Waiting Approval and then to Approved. - · WAPPR (Waiting Approval) is the default status for creating new Work Orders. In this status, a user can delete tasks, labor and materials with ease by using the Delete Row (trash can) icon and saving the record. However, a user cannot update the labor or materials information on the Actuals tab while the status is in Waiting on Approval. This is the only status in which a Job Plan can be applied or removed. - · WMATL (Waiting on Material) indicates materials must arrive before the work can

b while the status is in Waiting on Approval. This is the only status in which a Job Plan can be applied or removed. - · WMATL (Waiting on Material) indicates materials must arrive before the work can be performed. - · WPART (Waiting for Parts) indicates waiting for part before work can be performed or completed. - · WIRSC (Waiting for Internal Resources) indicates waiting for internal VA resources before work can be performed or completed. - · WCONT (Waiting for Contractor) indicates waiting for a contractor before work can be performed or completed. - · WOIT (Waiting for OIT) indicates waiting for OIT before work can be performed or completed. - · WVEND (Waiting for Vendor) indicates waiting for a vendor before work can be performed or completed. - · WPCOND (Waiting on Plant Condition) indicates you don't currently have access to the Asset or location, so the work cannot be performed until you do. NOTE: The waiting statuses should not be counted against Work Order aging metrics.
